description:
File: rust/lichen-rpl/src/message.rs
Lines: 171-184

The Dao::from_bytes() function assumes DODAGID is always present (D-flag=1) but does not validate this. Per RFC 6550 Section 6.4, if D=0, the DAO base is only 4 bytes (no DODAGID field). The current code unconditionally reads bytes 4..20 as dodag_id regardless of the D-flag value.

Impact: If a malformed or malicious DAO with D=0 is received, the parser will interpret option bytes as the DODAGID, leading to:
1. Incorrect DODAGID value (garbage data)
2. Option parsing starting at wrong offset
3. Potential security issues with misrouted packets

Fix: Check if D-flag (bit 6 of data[1]) is set. If D=0, reject with RplError::InvalidOption or handle the 4-byte DAO format.

Code:
```rust
pub fn from_bytes(data: &[u8]) -> Result<Self, RplError> {
    if data.len() < Self::BASE_LEN {
        return Err(TooShort::new(Self::BASE_LEN, data.len()).into());
    }
    let kd = data[1];
    // BUG: Missing validation - D-flag must be 1 for DODAGID to be present
    // let d_flag = (kd >> 6) & 1;
    // if d_flag == 0 { return Err(RplError::InvalidOption); }
    Ok(Self {
        rpl_instance_id: data[0],
        ack_requested: (kd >> 7) & 1 == 1,
        flags: kd & 0x3F,
        dao_sequence: data[3],
        dodag_id: data[4..20].try_into().unwrap(),  // Wrong if D=0
    })
}
```
